%%  §4  LH EVALUATION
%% =============================================================
\section{LH Evaluation}
\label{sec:eval}

\begin{figure*}
  \centering
  \includegraphics{lh_autopk.pdf}
  \caption{Auto-power spectra and fractional residuals on the LH test
    set ($N_{\rm sim}=100$, $n_{\rm gen}=30$ per sim).
    Solid black curves and grey bands show the CAMELS median and
    16--84 percentile range; dashed coloured curves and coloured bands
    show the corresponding \textsc{Genesis} statistics.
    The empirical cosmic-variance floor is shown as a grey residual
    envelope where plotted.
    The low-, mid-, and high-$k$ reporting bands are defined in
    Section~\ref{sec:metrics}; all band-averaged values in the text and
    tables use those boundaries.}
  \label{fig:lh_autopk}
\end{figure*}

This section evaluates \textsc{Genesis} on the 100 held-out LH test
simulations --- withheld entirely from training and validation and
spanning the full six-dimensional CAMELS parameter space.
Any failure to track cosmological or astrophysical variation manifests
directly in the residuals without averaging over parameter diversity ---
this makes the LH evaluation the primary test of generalisation across
the full design space.
Evaluation metrics are defined in Section~\ref{sec:metrics}; results
follow in Sections~\ref{sec:res_lh_summary} through~\ref{sec:res_r2},
with residuals assessed throughout relative to the cosmic-variance
floor defined in Section~\ref{sec:cv_floor}.

\begin{figure}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{lh_r2_scond.pdf}
  \caption{Conditional response and calibration on the LH test set.
    \emph{Left:} $R^2(k)$ of the generated $\log P(k)$ response to the
    six-dimensional conditioning vector.
    \emph{Right:} $S_{\rm cond}(k)$; the dashed line marks perfect
    calibration ($S_{\rm cond}=1$).
    Colours indicate $\Mcdm$, $\Mgas$, and $\Tgas$.}
  \label{fig:lh_r2_scond}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure*}
  \centering
  \includegraphics{lh_xi.pdf}
  \caption{Real-space two-point correlation function $\xi(r)$ on the LH
    test set ($N_{\rm sim}=100$, $n_{\rm gen}=30$ per sim).
    \emph{Top row:} $\xi(r)$ for CAMELS (black) and \textsc{Genesis} (coloured).
    \emph{Bottom row:} fractional residuals $\Delta\xi/|\xi|$.
    Panels show $\Mcdm$ (left), $\Mgas$ (centre), and $\Tgas$ (right).}
  \label{fig:lh_xi}
\end{figure*}

\subsection{Metrics}
\label{sec:metrics}

\textbf{Auto-power spectrum.}
For each field $a \in \{\Mcdm, \Mgas, \Tgas\}$ we compute the
azimuthally averaged 2D power spectrum $P_a(k)$ in 128 integer-rounded
wavenumber bins spanning the full range accessible by the $256^2$ map,
from the fundamental mode
$k_{\rm fund} \approx 0.25\,h\,\mathrm{Mpc}^{-1}$
to the Nyquist frequency $k_{\rm Ny} \approx 32\,h\,\mathrm{Mpc}^{-1}$.
For all band-averaged metrics reported in the text and tables, we group
the bins into three bands:
low-$k$ ($k < 1\,h\,\mathrm{Mpc}^{-1}$, 3 bins),
mid-$k$ ($1 \leq k < 5\,h\,\mathrm{Mpc}^{-1}$, 28 bins), and
high-$k$ ($5\,h\,\mathrm{Mpc}^{-1} \leq k < k_{\rm Ny}$, 33 bins);
bins at $k \geq k_{\rm Ny}$ are retained as a reference-only
artefact band.
The fractional residual is
\begin{equation}
  \DeltaP_a(k) =
  \frac{|\langle P_a^{\rm gen}(k)\rangle
       - \langle P_a^{\rm true}(k)\rangle|}
       {\langle P_a^{\rm true}(k)\rangle},
  \label{eq:dpp}
\end{equation}
reported separately for each of the three wavenumber bands.

\textbf{Cross-power spectrum.}
For each of the three field pairs
$(ab) \in \{(\Mcdm,\Mgas),\,(\Mcdm,\Tgas),\,(\Mgas,\Tgas)\}$ we
compute
\begin{equation}
  P_{ab}(k) = \mathrm{Re}\!\left[
    \langle \tilde{\delta}_a(\mathbf{k})\,
            \tilde{\delta}_b^*(\mathbf{k})\rangle
  \right]
  \label{eq:cross}
\end{equation}
and evaluate $\DeltaP_{ab}(k)$ as in equation~(\ref{eq:dpp}),
averaged over the three wavenumber bands.
The cross-power spectrum is the primary diagnostic of inter-field
correlations and provides a direct test of joint multifield fidelity;
a model that generates each channel independently would produce correct
marginals while failing this test.

\textbf{Inter-field coherence.}
The scale-dependent correlation coefficient
\begin{equation}
  r_{ab}(k) = \frac{P_{ab}(k)}{\sqrt{P_{aa}(k)\,P_{bb}(k)}}
  \label{eq:rab}
\end{equation}
isolates the structural inter-field relationship from amplitude effects,
probing whether the spatial patterns of the generated fields are
mutually consistent at each scale.
To our knowledge, $r_{ab}(k)$ has not been quantitatively evaluated in
any prior multifield cosmological generative model.
We report the maximum deviation
$\Delta r_{ab} = \max_k |r_{ab}^{\rm gen}(k) - r_{ab}^{\rm true}(k)|$
as a single worst-case summary per field pair.

\textbf{Pixel probability distribution function (PDF).}
The one-point pixel distribution is evaluated in $\log_{10}$ space using
the two-sample Kolmogorov--Smirnov (KS) statistic $D_{\rm KS}$, the
relative error on the mean
$\epsilon_\mu = |\mu_{\rm gen} - \mu_{\rm true}|/|\mu_{\rm true}|$, and
the relative error on the standard deviation
$\epsilon_\sigma = |\sigma_{\rm gen} - \sigma_{\rm true}|/
\sigma_{\rm true}$.
The temperature field exhibits a bimodal distribution --- cold gas
at $\sim10^4$~K and shock-heated halo plasma at
$\sim10^{6\text{--}7}$~K --- and we additionally verify that both
peaks are reproduced individually.

\textbf{Conditional power-spectrum response ($R^2$).}
To quantify how faithfully \textsc{Genesis} tracks the cosmology
dependence of the power spectrum, we compute the explained variance
ratio
\begin{equation}
  R^2(k) = 1 - \frac{\mathrm{MSE}_\theta[\log P_{\rm gen}(k)]}
                     {\mathrm{Var}_\theta[\log P_{\rm true}(k)]},
  \label{eq:r2}
\end{equation}
where the expectation is taken over the 100 LH test simulations.
$R^2 = 1$ indicates perfect tracking of the parameter-induced
variation; $R^2 = 0$ means the generated spectra carry no more
information about the conditioning vector than a constant prediction.

\textbf{Conditional calibration ($S_{\rm cond}$).}
We assess whether the generative spread is calibrated relative to the
true variability at each conditioning point using the mean squared
standardized residual
\begin{equation}
  S_{\rm cond}(k) = \left\langle
    \left(\frac{\log P_{\rm gen}(k;\thetavec)
               - \mu_{\rm true}(k;\thetavec)}
              {\sigma_{\rm true}(k;\thetavec)}\right)^2
  \right\rangle_{\thetavec},
  \label{eq:scond}
\end{equation}
where $\mu_{\rm true}$ and $\sigma_{\rm true}$ are the mean and
standard deviation of $\log P_{\rm true}$ computed from the 15 true
maps per simulation.
A perfectly calibrated generator gives $S_{\rm cond} = 1$; values
below (above) unity indicate underdispersion (overdispersion).

\textbf{Real-space two-point correlation function $\xi(r)$.}
As a complementary configuration-space probe, we compute $\xi(r)$ via
the inverse Fourier transform of the azimuthally averaged 2D power
spectrum, binned over 64 radial separations spanning
$0.1 \leq r \leq 12.5\,h^{-1}\,\mathrm{Mpc}$.
This statistic is sensitive to configuration-space clustering structure
beyond what the power spectrum captures and serves as an auxiliary
cross-check on the spectral results.

%% =============================================================
%%  §4.3  LH RESULTS
%% =============================================================
\subsection{LH quantitative summary}
\label{sec:res_lh_summary}

The hierarchy of residuals across the 100 LH test simulations reflects
the underlying physics directly --- dark matter, governed by gravity
alone, is the most predictable of the three fields, with auto-power
errors remaining closest to the cosmic-variance floor across all three
wavenumber bands.
The gas density field, shaped by both gravity and supernova wind
feedback, shows somewhat larger residuals at high $k$: the coupling
between density structure and stellar winds becomes more pronounced at
small scales.
The temperature field, as the most direct tracer of AGN heating and
shock structure, exhibits the largest residuals and the widest
inter-simulation scatter --- a consequence of the strong stochasticity
introduced by black-hole feedback across the six-dimensional parameter
space.
All three channels nevertheless remain below 8 per cent across the
high-$k$ band, indicating that \textsc{Genesis} captures the dominant
modes of variation throughout the full parameter space, including the
most feedback-sensitive observables.
Table~\ref{tab:lh_metrics} collects the auto-power residuals,
pixel-distribution statistics, and conditional response scores per
channel.

The cross-channel statistics further confirm joint multifield fidelity;
Table~\ref{tab:lh_cross} shows that mean cross-power residuals and
maximum coherence deviations remain well within acceptable bounds across
all field pairs and wavenumber bands.

