%%------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Field visualizations}
\label{sec:res_vis}

\textsc{Genesis} captures the principal structural features of each
field across five representative LH conditioning vectors
(Fig.~\ref{fig:lh_tiles}): the large-scale filamentary network and
dense halo cores of the dark matter, the clumpy, feedback-broadened
gas concentrated in high-density regions, and the broad cold--hot
temperature dichotomy between void gas and shock-heated halo plasma.
The generated samples are stochastic draws rather than exact
reconstructions of the same initial conditions as the CAMELS maps ---
such realization-level matching would require conditioning on the
initial density field, which lies outside the scope of this model ---
but they occupy the same morphological and statistical range at each
conditioning vector, with equivalent large-scale topology and comparable
small-scale contrast.

%%------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Power-spectrum fidelity}
\label{sec:res_auto}

The per-channel auto-power spectra and their fractional residuals are
shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:lh_autopk}, with the cosmic-variance floor
overlaid as a physical reference.
The dark matter channel achieves sub-3-per-cent accuracy in every
wavenumber band, with residuals that lie within or close to the CV
floor at most scales --- a strong result given that each generated map
must simultaneously satisfy conditioning on all six parameters spanning
the full LH design space.
The gas density and temperature channels, which carry the imprint of
supernova and AGN feedback, show larger residuals at high $k$, reaching
up to 8 per cent; this is consistent with the greater stochasticity of
baryonic fields at small scales, where feedback-driven outflows and
shock heating dominate the density and temperature structure.
At low and mid $k$, where the bulk of the cosmological information
resides, both fields track the true ensemble median faithfully.

%%------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Cross-field consistency}
\label{sec:res_cross}

Reproducing the correct marginal statistics for each channel in
isolation is a necessary but insufficient condition for a multifield
emulator: the joint distribution of the three fields must also be
internally consistent.
Fig.~\ref{fig:lh_cross_coherence} examines this through the
cross-power spectra and inter-field coherence.
Across all three field pairs and wavenumber bands, the generated
cross-power residuals remain below 7 per cent and the coherence
deviations below $0.04$ (Table~\ref{tab:lh_cross}).
The largest deviations arise in the $\Mcdm$--$\Tgas$ pair at high $k$;
even here, the coherence remains within $0.03$, suggesting that
\textsc{Genesis} has internalized the conditional coupling between
the fields rather than generating them independently.
AGN-driven heating introduces stochastic temperature fluctuations
at small scales that are only weakly tied to the local dark-matter
density --- this coupling makes the $\Mcdm$--$\Tgas$ pair the most
demanding test of joint generation.

\begin{figure*}
  \centering
  \includegraphics{lh_cross_coherence.pdf}
  \caption{\emph{Top row:} LH cross-power spectra $P_{ab}(k)$ for the
    three field pairs ($\Mcdm$--$\Mgas$, $\Mcdm$--$\Tgas$, $\Mgas$--$\Tgas$).
    \emph{Bottom row:} inter-field coherence $r_{ab}(k)$ for the same
    pairs.
    Black curves show CAMELS statistics and dashed coloured curves show
    \textsc{Genesis}; shaded regions show 16--84 percentile ranges over
    the LH test ensemble.}
  \label{fig:lh_cross_coherence}
\end{figure*}

%%------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{One-point and configuration-space statistics}
\label{sec:res_pdf}

Beyond power spectra, the one-point pixel distribution tests whether
the full amplitude range of the fields is correctly reproduced,
including the rare high-density and high-temperature tails that are not
directly constrained by two-point statistics.
The KS statistics across the 100 LH test simulations lie in the range
$0.035$--$0.048$, and the JSD values are below $5\times10^{-3}$ for all
three channels (Table~\ref{tab:lh_pdf}; Appendix
Fig.~\ref{fig:figs5a}).
The temperature channel is the most challenging: its bimodal
distribution, with cold gas at $\sim10^4$~K and shock-heated halo
plasma at $\sim10^{6\text{--}7}$~K, requires the model to reproduce
two physically distinct regimes simultaneously.
Both peaks are present in the generated maps, and the per-simulation
field means cluster tightly around the $y=x$ diagonal (Appendix
Fig.~\ref{fig:figs5b}), confirming that the mean amplitude is correctly
tracked across the full LH parameter range.

The real-space correlation function $\xi(r)$, computed as an auxiliary
configuration-space check, agrees closely with the true profiles across
all three channels (Fig.~\ref{fig:lh_xi}), consistent with the spectral
results above.
The fractional residuals $\Delta\xi/|\xi|$ are well-behaved at
$r \lesssim 7\,h^{-1}\,\mathrm{Mpc}$, where $|\xi_{\rm true}|$ is
sufficiently large for the ratio to be well-defined; at larger
separations $\xi_{\rm true}$ approaches zero and undergoes a sign
change; the fractional residual therefore diverges regardless of
model accuracy.

\input{figuers/table3_lh_pdf.tex}

%%------------------------------------------------------------
\subsection{Conditional response and calibration}
\label{sec:res_r2}

A generative model that reproduces mean statistics without tracking
their parameter dependence would be of limited use for
simulation-based inference.
Fig.~\ref{fig:lh_r2_scond} tests this through the $R^2$ and
$S_{\rm cond}$ diagnostics.
The overall $R^2$ scores are $0.845$, $0.877$, and $0.823$ for
$\Mcdm$, $\Mgas$, and $\Tgas$, respectively, indicating that
\textsc{Genesis} explains the majority of the parameter-induced
variance in the generated power spectra across the full LH design
space.
The lowest values occur at large scales, where the small simulation
volume produces the largest sample variance and the conditioning signal
is relatively weak; the response improves consistently toward smaller
scales.
The $S_{\rm cond}$ values for the gas and temperature channels are
mildly above unity at high $k$, reflecting modest overdispersion rather
than a systematic bias --- the generated ensemble is slightly broader
than the true per-simulation scatter at small scales, a behaviour
consistent with the elevated stochasticity of baryonic fields in the
feedback-sensitive regime.
For simulation-based inference applications, this mild overdispersion
implies that generated samples will slightly overestimate the
per-simulation scatter at small scales; the effect is small enough
that it is unlikely to bias parameter posteriors at the scales where
cosmological information is concentrated.

%%------------------------------------------------------------
\section{CV Evaluation}
\label{sec:cv_eval}

\begin{figure*}
  \centering
  \includegraphics{cv_tiles.pdf}
  \caption{Representative CV map triplets at the fiducial conditioning
    vector ($\Om=0.30$, $\sig=0.80$, all $A=1$).
    Each row shows one true CAMELS realization alongside five independent
    \textsc{Genesis} samples generated at the same conditioning vector.
    All maps are shown in $\log_{10}$ space.}
  \label{fig:cv_tiles}
\end{figure*}

Where the LH evaluation asks how well \textsc{Genesis} generalises
across parameter space, the CV evaluation asks a more fundamental
question: at a fixed cosmology, are the generated samples statistically
indistinguishable from an additional draw from the true simulation
ensemble?
This is a stronger condition than matching mean power spectra, and it
is directly relevant for simulation-based inference pipelines that
treat generated samples as stand-ins for new simulations at the same
parameter point.

\subsection{Cosmic variance as a physical lower bound}
\label{sec:cv_floor}

Any $P(k)$ estimate from a finite-volume simulation carries
irreducible scatter: $\mathrm{Var}[P(k_i)] \geq 2P(k_i)^2 /
N_{\rm modes}(k_i)$, where $N_{\rm modes}(k_i)$ counts the
independent Fourier modes in annular bin $i$ --- a bound that a
generative model trained on the same volume cannot escape.
Sub-floor accuracy is therefore physically meaningless; the
cosmic-variance floor sets the natural ceiling for emulator fidelity.

We estimate this floor from the 27 CAMELS CV simulations, which share
the fiducial cosmology
$(\Om,\,\sig,\,A_{\rm SN1},\,A_{\rm SN2},\,A_{\rm AGN1},\,A_{\rm AGN2})
=(0.30,\,0.80,\,1,\,1,\,1,\,1)$
and differ only in their initial conditions --- their inter-realization
scatter thereby isolates finite-volume noise without contamination from
parameter variation.
The field-level floor is defined as
\begin{equation}
  \sigma_{{\rm CV},a}(k_i) =
  \mathrm{std}_{j}\!\bigl[P_a^{(j)}(k_i)\bigr],
  \quad j = 1,\ldots,27,
  \label{eq:cv_floor}
\end{equation}
and serves as a physical reference throughout both
Section~\ref{sec:eval} and the CV analyses that follow.

\subsection{CV dataset and leave-one-out construction}
\label{sec:res_cv}

Each of the 27 CV simulations introduced above contributes 15
independent maps; \textsc{Genesis} is evaluated against 200 generated
maps drawn at the same conditioning vector.

The evaluation adopts a leave-one-out (LOO) construction to place the
model and the true simulations on an equal footing.
For each CV simulation $j \in \{1,\ldots,27\}$, a null distribution of
test statistics is built by treating simulation $j$ as a held-out probe:
the maps of simulation $j$ are passed through the same evaluation
pipeline that is applied to the generated ensemble, while the remaining
26 simulations define the reference distribution.
Repeating this procedure for every $j$ yields 27 null statistics
$\{T_1,\ldots,T_{27}\}$ that quantify the natural
simulation-to-simulation scatter at the fiducial cosmology.
The model statistic $T_{\rm model}$, computed from the 200 generated
maps against the full 27-simulation reference, is then compared to this
null distribution.
The logic is that a well-calibrated generative model should produce a
$T_{\rm model}$ that is indistinguishable from one of the $T_j$ values
--- it should look like another simulation, not like an outlier from the
ensemble.

We classify $T_{\rm model}$ as \emph{natural} if it lies within the
central 68 per cent interval $[p_{16},p_{84}]$ of the null distribution,
\emph{caution} if it falls in the adjacent
$[p_5,p_{16}) \cup (p_{84},p_{95}]$ tails, and \emph{alarm} if it lies
outside $[p_5,p_{95}]$.
The natural classification therefore corresponds to the model performing
no worse than a typical held-out simulation.

In addition to the auto-power, cross-power, coherence, and one-point
statistics defined in Section~\ref{sec:metrics}, the CV stage introduces
two further diagnostics.
The power-spectrum displacement
\begin{equation}
  \Delta_{\rm CV}(k) =
    \frac{\bar{P}_{\rm gen}(k) - \bar{P}_{\rm LOO}(k)}
         {\bar{P}_{\rm LOO}(k)}
  \label{eq:dcv}
\end{equation}
measures the fractional offset of the generated ensemble mean from the
LOO reference mean at each wavenumber.
The variance ratio
\begin{equation}
  R_\sigma(k) =
    \frac{\operatorname{Var}_{\rm gen}[\log P(k)]}
         {\operatorname{Var}_{\rm LOO}[\log P(k)]}
  \label{eq:rsigma}
\end{equation}
tests whether the sample-to-sample scatter of the generated power
spectra matches that of the true CV ensemble; $R_\sigma = 1$ indicates
perfect agreement in dispersion.

Since all 27 CV simulations share the same parameters, the relevant
question is not whether individual maps match but whether the diversity
of the generated ensemble is morphologically consistent with that of
the true ensemble.
Representative true and generated triplets at the fiducial conditioning
vector are shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:cv_tiles}.

\subsection{CV spectral consistency}
\label{sec:cv_spectra}

The generated ensemble tracks both the median and the
inter-realization spread of the true CV suite across all three channels
and wavenumber bands (Fig.~\ref{fig:cv_auto_pk}).
The $k$-dependent LOO statistics $\Delta_{\rm CV}(k)$ and $R_\sigma(k)$
confirm this: the displacement remains close to zero at all scales, and
the variance ratio is consistent with unity, indicating that the
generated ensemble neither over-concentrates nor over-disperses relative
to the true CV scatter (Fig.~\ref{fig:cv_dcv_rsigma}).

The LOO classification results, summarised in Table~\ref{tab:cv_loo},
show that $T_{\rm model}$ falls within the natural $[p_{16},p_{84}]$
band for all combinations of statistic, field, and wavenumber band.
Cross-power spectra and inter-field coherence at the fiducial cosmology
are shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:cv_cross_coherence}; all three field pairs
pass the natural classification across low-, mid-, and high-$k$ bands.
The fact that $T_{\rm model}$ passes the natural classification
across all statistics, fields, and scale bands --- equivalent to
being indistinguishable from a held-out simulation --- supports
the use of \textsc{Genesis} as a drop-in replacement for new
simulations at the fiducial cosmology in downstream inference
pipelines.

\begin{figure*}
  \centering
  \includegraphics{cv_auto_pk.pdf}
  \caption{CV auto-power spectra $P_a(k)$ and fractional residuals for
    the 27 simulations at the fiducial cosmology
    ($N_{\rm sim}=27$, $n_{\rm gen}=200$).
    Thin grey lines show individual true simulations; the thick black
    line shows their ensemble median; dashed coloured curves and bands
    show the \textsc{Genesis} ensemble median and 16--84 percentile
    range.
    Panels show $\Mcdm$ (left), $\Mgas$ (centre), and $\Tgas$ (right).}
  \label{fig:cv_auto_pk}
\end{figure*}

\input{figuers/table2_cv_loo.tex}

\begin{figure}
  \centering
  \includegraphics{cv_dcv_rsigma.pdf}
  \caption{CV LOO test statistics as functions of wavenumber
    ($N_{\rm sim}=27$, $n_{\rm gen}=200$).
    \emph{Left:} power-spectrum displacement $\Delta_{\rm CV}(k)$
    (equation~\ref{eq:dcv}); dashed lines mark $\pm 1$.
    \emph{Right:} variance ratio $R_\sigma(k)$
    (equation~\ref{eq:rsigma}); the solid line marks $R_\sigma=1$.
    Colours indicate $\Mcdm$, $\Mgas$, and $\Tgas$ as in
    Fig.~\ref{fig:cv_auto_pk}.}
  \label{fig:cv_dcv_rsigma}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure*}
  \centering
  \includegraphics{cv_cross_coherence.pdf}
  \caption{CV cross-power spectra and inter-field coherence at the
    fiducial cosmology ($N_{\rm sim}=27$, $n_{\rm gen}=200$).
    \emph{Top row:} cross-power $P_{ab}(k)$ for the three field pairs.
    \emph{Bottom row:} coherence $r_{ab}(k)$ for the same pairs.
    Grey curves show the 27 individual true CV simulations; dashed
    coloured curves and bands show the \textsc{Genesis} ensemble.
    All model values pass the LOO natural classification.}
  \label{fig:cv_cross_coherence}
\end{figure*}

\subsection{CV one-point consistency}
\label{sec:cv_1pt}

The one-point pixel distributions at the fiducial cosmology are shown
in Fig.~\ref{fig:cv_1pt}.
For all three channels, the generated pixel distributions are consistent
with the spread of the true CV ensemble, confirming that the full
amplitude range of the fields is reproduced and not merely the
two-point statistics.
The ensemble standard deviations are slightly broader for $\Mcdm$ and
$\Tgas$ than for the true CV set, consistent with the mild
overdispersion observed in $S_{\rm cond}$ at high $k$ in the LH analysis
(Section~\ref{sec:res_r2}).
This should be read as a mild caution on per-pixel dispersion rather
than a failure of the spectral CV protocol: the spectral statistics all
pass the natural LOO classification, and the one-point broadening
remains well within the inter-simulation scatter of the true ensemble.

\begin{figure}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{cv_pixel_pdf.pdf}
  \caption{CV pixel-value distributions in $\log_{10}$ space at the
    fiducial cosmology ($N_{\rm sim}=27$, $n_{\rm gen}=200$).
    Grey filled histograms show the pooled CAMELS CV distribution;
    coloured histograms show the \textsc{Genesis} ensemble.
    Panels show $\Mcdm$ (left), $\Mgas$ (centre), and $\Tgas$ (right).}
  \label{fig:cv_1pt}
\end{figure}

%% =============================================================
%%  §6  DISCUSSION
%% =============================================================
\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

The evaluations of Sections~\ref{sec:eval} and \ref{sec:cv_eval}
demonstrate that
\textsc{Genesis} reproduces single-field and multifield statistics
across the full CAMELS parameter space and passes both validation
protocols evaluated in this work (LH and CV).
In this section we examine the architectural and methodological factors
underlying this performance (Section~\ref{sec:disc_arch}), interpret
the proximity to the cosmic variance floor
(Section~\ref{sec:disc_cv}), place \textsc{Genesis} in the context of
prior work (Section~\ref{sec:disc_comparison}), and identify the
principal limitations of the current implementation
(Section~\ref{sec:disc_limitations}).

\subsection{Multi-field stability and the role of architecture}
\label{sec:disc_arch}

The stable cross-power fidelity of \textsc{Genesis} across the full
parameter space --- including regions where GAN-based emulators have
shown sensitivity to parameter combinations
\citep{Andrianomena2024} --- can be attributed to two complementary
factors.
First, the OT flow-matching objective provides a smooth, well-defined
transport map between Gaussian noise and the target data distribution,
without the adversarial instability that makes GAN training sensitive
to specific regions of parameter space.
This is consistent with the broader finding that diffusion and flow
matching models recover statistical properties more uniformly than GANs
\citep{Aoyama2025}.
Second, the architecture combines stage-wise conditioning with
multi-scale attention, allowing the generated fields to respond to the
full six-dimensional parameter vector while still preserving long-range
cross-field structure.
This is particularly important for the $\Mgas$--$\Tgas$ cross-power,
where the correlation is weaker than $\Mcdm$--$\Mgas$ and more
sensitive to the feedback parameter values.
The circular convolution design is motivated by the periodic boundary
conditions of the simulation box and has the practical advantage that it
prevents boundary leakage artefacts in the generated fields.
Although we cannot isolate its contribution from a single ablation, it
is consistent with earlier use of periodic padding in cosmological
U-Nets \citep[e.g.][]{Jamieson2022}.

\subsection{Proximity to the cosmic variance floor}
\label{sec:disc_cv}

The fact that $\Mcdm$ auto-power residuals approach the CV floor is
physically significant.
It implies that \textsc{Genesis} has extracted much of the
information available in the $25\,h^{-1}$~Mpc CAMELS training volume
for this field: further reducing the mean fractional error would
require training data from a larger
simulation volume with a lower cosmic variance floor.
For $\Mgas$ and $\Tgas$, the CV floors are higher due to the stronger
influence of feedback stochasticity, and residuals remain somewhat above
the floor, indicating room for improvement in capturing small-scale
baryonic physics.

\subsection{Comparison with prior multifield work}
\label{sec:disc_comparison}

\textsc{Genesis} differs from prior field-level generative models in
several key respects.
Unlike field-to-field translation approaches
\citep{Mishra2026,Horowitz2025} that condition on an input field rather
than directly on simulation parameters, \textsc{Genesis} simultaneously
generates three fields conditioned on six parameters.
It is also the first model to (1) quantitatively evaluate inter-field
coherence $r_{ab}(k)$ and (2) pass both the LH and CV validation
protocols, with the CV leave-one-out test confirming cosmic-variance
consistency.
The cross-power stability of \textsc{Genesis} across all parameter
combinations may be compared with the conditional GAN of
\citet{Andrianomena2024}, which reported cross-power $R^2$ values as
low as $-11.93$ for specific $(\Om, \sig)$ combinations --- a regime
where adversarial training is susceptible to mode collapse.

